What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consist of 113,036 rows and 18 columns. After checking for duplicate it was discovered that there are 1000 duplicated values. After removing it became 112,036 rows and 18 columns.They consist of 10 quantitative variables namely: Day, Year, Customer_Age,Order Quantity, UNit_Cost, Unit_price, Profit, Cost and Revenue and Categorical variables namely gender, state, country, products,Product_Category, Sub_Category and month.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in looking at factors/variables that influences sales. I am also keen to know the age group that buys different products and which country and states produces the highest revenue and profit.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think age of customer will countribute significantly to the sales of bike and profit the store makes. The younger people might tend to purchase more than the old people. Also, the cost might also influence the sales.

In [6]:
# We can as well transform using the Log scale since it has a long tail distribution
log_binsize = 0.055
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df_sales['Revenue'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_sales, x = 'Revenue', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([ 200, 400, 600, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3,], [200, 400,600, '1k', '2k', '5k'])
plt.xlabel('Revenue ($)')
plt.show()

Revenue is almost bimodal here with a little difference, and customers revenue between 50 and 5000.

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.055
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df_sales['Profit'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_sales, x = 'Profit', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([ 300, 400, 500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3,], [300, 400,500, '1k', '2k', '5k'])
plt.xlabel('Profit ($)')
plt.show()

Profit has a long taied distribution here, with most profit between 250 and 1000. Also with few around 1000-2000. Howerver, when I plotted on log-scale, the profit distribution looks unimodal. From the distribution 400 happens to have the highest mode.

plt.figure(figsize = [15, 8])

# left histogram: data plotted in natural units
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
bin_edges = np.arange(0, df_sales_sub['Revenue'].max()+1000, 1000)
plt.hist(data =df_sales_sub, x = 'Revenue', bins = bin_edges)
plt.xlabel('Revenue')
plt.ylabel('Count');
plt.title("Revenue from all Customer");

# right histogram: data plotted after direct log transformation
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
log_data = np.log10(df_sales_sub['Revenue']) # direct data transform
log_bin_edges = np.arange(3, log_data.max()+0.5, 0.025)
plt.hist(log_data, bins = log_bin_edges)
plt.xlabel('log(Revenue from all customers)');
plt.ylabel('Count');
plt.title("Revenue from all Customers (Log)");

The log transform plot looks better.

# Get the counts of each unique age
age_counts = df_sales['Customer_Age'].value_counts()

# Select the 20 most frequent ages
top_20_ages = age_counts.nlargest(20)

# Plotting the countplot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data=df_sales, x='Customer_Age', color=base_color, order=top_20_ages.index)

# Adding labels and title to the plot
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Frequency_count")
plt.title("Top 20 Most Frequent Customer Ages")

# Rotating x-axis labels if needed
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Displaying the plot
plt.show()

# since there's only three subplots to create, using the full data should be fine.
plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])

# subplot 1: color vs cut
plt.subplot(3, 1, 1)
sb.countplot(data = df_sales, x = 'Age_Group', hue = 'Customer_Gender', palette = 'Blues')

# subplot 2: clarity vs. cut
ax = plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)
sb.countplot(data = df_sales, x = 'Product_Category', hue = 'Customer_Gender', palette = 'Blues')
ax.legend(ncol = 2) # re-arrange legend to reduce overlapping

# subplot 3: clarity vs. color, use different color palette

In [14]:
#creating a boxgrid function
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """
    Function for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid.
    """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color=default_color)

def boxplot_grid(data, y_vars, x_vars):
    """
    Function to create a PairGrid plot with box plots.
    
    Args:
        data (df_sales)
        y_vars (list): List of variables to be plotted on the y-axis.
        x_vars (list): List of variables to be plotted on the x-axis.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=[12, 8])
    g = sb.PairGrid(data=data, y_vars=y_vars, x_vars=x_vars,
                    size=4, aspect=1.5)
    g.map(boxgrid)
    plt.show()

df_filtered = df_sales[(df_sales['Year'] >= 2011) & (df_sales['Year'] <= 2016)]
In [23]:
profit_by_year_gender = df_filtered.groupby(['Year', 'Customer_Gender'])['Profit'].sum()
In [26]:
years = profit_by_year_gender.index.levels[0]
genders = profit_by_year_gender.index.levels[1]

# Create a figure with size 8x6
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Loop over each gender
for gender in genders:
    profits = profit_by_year_gender.loc[:, gender]
    # Plot the profits for each year
    plt.plot(years, profits, marker='o', linestyle='-', label=gender)

# Set the title, x-label, and y-label
plt.title('Profit over the years by Customer Gender')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Profit')

# Add a legend, grid, and display the plot
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

From the visualisation above, it is clear that profit keeps rising until 2015 where it drops among female customers and remain the same for the male counterpart
